920. Dicam ut. Mil. 1191 Eyo illi diesem ut ‘me adiutorem, qui onus feram ad portum, roget, Men. 1044 dicam ut α me abeat liber quo uolet, Pers. 281. Cf. v. 397 above. Penum aliud.. The Neuter Gender is attested by Priscian, while the form penum is confirmed by the agreement of the Ambrosian Palimpsest with the other MSS. (cf. erile penum Afran. Com. 329 R). The adornet apparently offered by A may be due to con- fusion with adornat of the following line. 1 hesitate to admit the form alid of Lucr. i. 263. Studemund favoured alibi, corresponding to laic in v. 921, 1116 Adverb ‘here’ Leo reads penum alium adornet, supposing the Neuter Gender of the word to be a gramniatical fiction, due to the Early Latin fashion of writing -e for -z's <but see my note on V. 518).
